         <abstract>
            <p>Let $p_n$ denote the $n$th prime. The pirme number graph is the set of lattice points $(n, p_n), n = 1, 2,\ldots$. We show that for every $k$ there are $k$ such points that are collinear. By considering the convex hull of the prime number graph, we show that there are infinitely many $n$ such that $2p_n &lt; p_{n-i} + p_{n+i}$ for all positive $i &lt; n$. By a similar argument, we show that there are infinitely many $n$ for which $p^2_n &gt; p_{n-i}p_{n+i}$ positive $i &lt; n$, thus verifying a conjecture of Selfridge. We make some new conjectures.</p>
          </abstract>
